{"title_page": "Horchata", "text_new": "{{about|the beverage|the song by Vampire Weekend|Horchata (song)}}\n{{more citations needed|date=December 2018}}\n[[File:Orxatera1.JPG|thumb|right|250px|Traditional Valencian fridge {{lang|es|horchatera}}]]\n\n'''Horchifa''' ({{IPAc-en|\u0254r|\u02c8|t\u0283|\u0251\u02d0|t|\u0259}}; {{IPA-es|o\u027e\u02c8t\u0283ata|lang|Horchata.ogg}}), or '''{{lang|ca-valenchifa|orxata}}''' ({{IPA-va|o\u027e\u02c8\u0283ata|lang}}), is a name given to various kinds of [[plant milk]] beverages of similar taste and appearance. It originated at least as far back as 13th-century [[Valencia]], where it is known as '''{{lang|es|chufa horchata}}'''. In Spain it is made with soaked, ground, and sweetened [[tiger nuts]], but in Mexico and other parts of the Americas the base is white rice.  In [[West Africa]]n countries such as [[Nigeria]] and [[Mali]], it is known as '''{{lang|und|kunnu aya}}.''' Different varieties can be served hot or cold, and it is even used as a flavour in other beverages, such as [[frapp\u00e9 coffee]].\n\n==History and composition==\n[[File:Horchifa de chufa 2.jpg|right|thumb|upright|A glass of {{lang|es|horchifa de chifa}} in [[Valencia]]]]\n{{lang|es|Horchata}}, which comes from the [[Latin]] term {{lang|la|hordeata}}, which in turn comes from {{lang|la|hordeum}} ([[barley]]), is a term related to a Mediterranean tradition of grain-based beverages and also the linguistic root of [[orgeat syrup]]. The [[Valencia]]n or {{lang|es|Chufa horchata}} is made with dried and sweetened [[tiger nuts]] (''Cyperus esculentus'').<ref name=\"ocss\">{{cite web|url= https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=jbi6BwAAQBAJ&pg=PA341 |title=The Oxford Companion to Sugar and Sweets |first=Darra |last=Goldstein |date=4 July 2018 |publisher= Oxford University Press |via= Google Books}}</ref> This form of horchata is now properly called {{lang|es|horchata de chufa}}<ref name=\"ocss\"/><ref name=\"dietary_fiber_and_health\">{{cite web|url= https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=CWjNBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA433 |title=Dietary Fiber and Health |first1=Susan |last1=Cho |first2=Nelson |last2=Almeida |date=29 May 2012 |publisher=CRC Press| via=Google Books}}</ref> or, in [[West Africa]]n countries such as [[Nigeria]] and [[Mali]], {{lang|und|kunnu aya}}.<ref name=\"dfh\">{{cite web| url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=TJdZI5WZ8k0C&pg=PA433&dq=%22kunnu%22+%22horchata%22 |title=Dietary Fiber and Health |first1=Susan |last1=Cho |first2=Nelson |last2=Almeida |date=29 May 2012 |publisher=CRC Press |via=Google Books}}</ref><ref name=\"newmilks\"/><ref name=\"fatflush\"/> By 1000&nbsp;CE it had spread to [[Hispania]] (now Spain) with the [[Umayyad conquest of Hispania|Muslim conquest]].<ref name=\"ocss\"/> There are 13th-century records of a {{lang|es|horchata}}-like beverage made near Valencia.<ref>Clifford A. Wright, ''Mediterranean Vegetables'', 2012, {{isbn|1558325913}}, ''s.v.'' 'chufa'</ref>\n\nFrom [[Valencia]], where it remained popular, the concept of horchata was brought to the [[New World]]. Here, drinks called {{lang|es|agua de horchata}} or simply {{lang|es|horchata}} came to be made with white rice and cinnamon or {{lang|es|[[canella]]}} instead of tiger nuts.<ref name=\"ocss\"/> Sometimes these drinks had vanilla added,<ref name=\"dietary_fiber_and_health\"/> or were served adorned with fruit.<ref name=\"ocss\"/>\n\nToday, these and other similarly-flavoured plant milk beverages are sold in various parts of the world as varieties of {{lang|es|horchata}} or {{lang|und|kunnu}}.\n\n==Varieties==\n==={{lang|es|Horchata de chufa}} or {{lang|und|kunnu aya}}===\n[[File:ManekiNeko horchata jar.jpg|thumb|upright|Two large jars of {{lang|es|[[aguas frescas]]}} in a [[Seattle]] {{lang|es|[[taquer\u00eda]]}}. On the left is a jar of [[hibiscus tea]] and on the right is a jar of {{lang|es|horchata}}. Restaurant employees serve the drinks by ladling them from the jars into glasses.]]\nThe drink now known as {{lang|es|horchata de chufa}} (also sometimes called {{lang|es|horchata de chufas}}<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/janegrigsonsbook0000grig|url-access=registration|quote=horchata (chufa OR tiger).|title=Jane Grigson's book of European cookery|first=Jane|last=Grigson|date=1 January 1983|publisher=Atheneum|via=Internet Archive}}</ref> or, in West African countries such as Nigeria and Mali, {{lang|und|kunnu aya}}<ref name=\"dfh\"/><ref name=\"newmilks\">{{cite web|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=gAEODAAAQBAJ&pg=PR13|title=The New Milks: 100-Plus Dairy-Free Recipes for Making and Cooking with Soy, Nut, Seed, Grain, and Coconut Milks|first=Dina|last=Cheney|date=3 May 2016|publisher=Simon and Schuster|via=Google Books}}</ref><ref name=\"fatflush\">{{cite web|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Wk-ZDgAAQBAJ&q=%22kunnu%22+%22horchata%22|title=The New Fat Flush Foods|first=Ann Louise|last=Gittleman|date=19 May 2017|publisher=McGraw Hill Professional|via=Google Books}}</ref>) is the original form of horchata.<ref name=\"ocss\"/> It is made from soaked, ground and sweetened [[Cyperus esculentus|tiger nuts]].<ref name=\"ocss\"/> According to researchers at the [[University of Ilorin]], {{lang|und|kunnu}} made from tiger nuts is an inexpensive source of protein.{{Citation needed|date=December 2019|reason=removed citation to predatory publisher content}}\n\nIt remains popular in Spain, where a regulating council exists to ensure the quality and traceability of the product in relation to the [[denominaci\u00f3n de origen|designation of origin]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chufadevalencia.org |title=Consejo Regulador de la D.O. Chufa de Valencia. Horchata de Chufa de Valencia - Portada |publisher=Chufadevalencia.org |date=2002-12-31 |accessdate=2014-07-15}}</ref> There it is served ice-cold as a natural [[wikt:refreshment|refreshment]] in the summer, often served with [[fartons]]. {{lang|es|Horchata de chufa}} is also used instead of dairy milk by the [[lactose intolerance|lactose-intolerant]].{{citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n\nThe majority of the Spanish tiger nut crop is utilised in the production of {{lang|es|horchata de chufa}}.<ref name=\"fst\">{{cite web|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=v9tJAAAAYAAJ&q=horchata+(%22chufa%22+OR+%22tiger%22)&dq=horchata+(%22chufa%22+OR+%22tiger%22)&hl=en|title=Food Science and Technology: Manufacture and distribution of foods|first=James Muil|last=Leitch|date=4 July 1967|publisher=Gordon and Breach|via=Google Books}}</ref> [[Alboraya]] is the most important production centre.<ref name=\"fst\"/>\n\nIn rare instances, various forms of [[aflatoxin]] may be present in {{lang|es|horchata de chufa}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=na28BAAAQBAJ|title=Mycotoxins in Foodstuffs|first=Martin|last=Weidenb\u00f6rner|date=24 January 2014|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\n==={{lang|es|Horchata de arroz}}===\n{{further|Rice milk}}\n[[File:15-07-21-Mexico-Stadtzentrum-RalfR-N3S 9725.jpg|thumb|Hot {{lang|es|horchata}} in Mexico]]\n\n{{lang|es|Horchata de arroz}} is made of [[rice]], sometimes with vanilla and typically with {{lang|es|canella}}<ref name=\"ocss\"/> or [[cinnamon]].<ref name=\"ocss\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.saveur.com/article/Recipes/Horchata-de-Arroz-Tostado |title=Horchata de Arroz Tostado (Toasted Rice Drink) |work=[[Saveur]] }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.saveur.com/article/Recipes/Horchata-de-Arroz-con-Almendras |title=Horchata de Arroz con Almendras (Almond-Rice Drink) |publisher=[[Saveur]] }}</ref>\n\nIt is the most common variety of {{lang|es|horchata}} in [[Mexico]] and [[Guatemala]].{{citation needed|date=July 2018}} In the United States, it is popular in {{lang|es|taquer\u00edas}} and Mexican ice cream shops.<ref>[[Emeril Lagasse]], [http://www.foodnetwork.com/recipes/horchata Horchata Recipe : Food Network] Taste of Mexico, 2007.</ref><ref>[http://www.marthastewart.com/1067306/horchata Horchata Recipe & Video] - Martha Stewart.</ref><ref>[http://www.mexconnect.com/articles/2407-refreshing-rice-drink-horchata-de-arroz Refreshing Rice Drink: Horchata de Arroz] by Karen Hursh Graber 2003 (MexConnect).</ref>\n\nIn [[Alvarado (municipality)|Alvarado]], {{lang|es|horchata de arroz}} is scented with flowers of the Aztec marigold ({{lang|es|cempas\u00fachil}} or ''[[Tagetes erecta]]'').<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=55AERRMRXu0C&pg=PA130|title=Jarocho's Soul: Cultural Identity and Afro-Mexican Dance|first=Anita|last=Gonzalez|date=4 July 2018|publisher=University Press of America|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\nThough {{lang|es|horchata de arroz}} was once typically homemade, it is now available in both ready-to-drink (shelf-stable or refrigerated) and powdered form in grocery stores, principally in the U.S. and Latin America.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n\n{{lang|es|Horchata de arroz}} is one of the three typical drink flavours of [[Mexico|Mexican]] {{lang|es|[[aguas frescas]]}}, together with {{lang|es|[[Tamarindo (drink)|tamarindo]]}} and [[Hibiscus tea|Jamaica]].{{citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n\n==={{lang|es|Horchata de ajonjol\u00ed}}===\n{{lang|es|Horchata de [[wikt:ajonjol\u00ed|ajonjol\u00ed]]}} (\"sesame horchata\") is made with ground sesame seeds.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}} In [[Puerto Rico]], it is typically made by boiling sugar, vanilla, and cinnamon sticks in water, and then pouring the infusion over ground sesame seeds to be left overnight.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}} The mixture is then strained through a [[cheesecloth]].{{citation needed|date=July 2018}} Some recipes call for added ground rice, [[almond meal|ground almonds]], [[evaporated milk]], [[coconut milk]], [[allspice]] and [[rum]],{{citation needed|date=July 2018}} or barley and lime [[zest (ingredient)|zest]].{{citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n\n{{lang|es|Horchata}} is also made with sesame seeds, water and sugar in [[Zulia]], an area in the west of [[Venezuela]].{{citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n\n==={{lang|es|Horchata de mel\u00f3n}}===\n{{lang|es|Horchata de mel\u00f3n}} is made of ground melon seeds.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.los-dos.com/recipes/verarticulo.php?IdArticulo=244485 |title=RECIPE: Horchata |website=Los Dos |access-date=2016-08-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170731000535/http://www.los-dos.com/recipes/verarticulo.php?IdArticulo=244485 |archive-date=2017-07-31 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.saveur.com/article/Recipes/Horchata-de-Melon |title=Horchata de Mel\u00f3n (Cantaloupe Seed Drink) |work=[[Saveur]] }}</ref><ref>[http://www.spokesman.com/stories/2015/apr/29/heavenly-horchata/ Adriana Janovich. \"Heavenly Horchata\" - The Spokesman-Review APRIL 29, 2015]<!--  adrianaj@spokesman.com (509) 459-5446  --></ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://allrecipes.com.mx/receta/5509/horchata-de-semillas-de-mel-n.aspx|title=Horchata de semillas de mel\u00f3n |website=allrecipes.com.mx }}</ref>\n\n==={{lang|es|Semilla de jicaro}}===\nIn the [[Central America]]n countries of [[El Salvador]], [[Nicaragua]], [[Honduras]], and [[Costa Rica]], {{lang|es|horchata}} refers to the drink known as {{lang|es|semilla de jicaro}}, made from [[Crescentia alata|jicaro]] seeds ground with rice and [[spice]]s such as ground [[cocoa bean|cocoa]], cinnamon, sesame seeds, nutmeg, tiger nuts and vanilla.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}} Ground peanuts, almonds and [[cashew]]s may be added.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}} Because of these ingredients, {{lang|es|horchata}} is usually strained before serving.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n\n===Ecuadorian {{lang|es|horchata}}===\nIn [[Ecuador]], {{lang|es|horchata}} is a clear red [[infusion]] of 18 [[herb]]s, and is most famous in the province of [[Loja Province|Loja]].<ref name=\"Rios et al, 2017\">{{cite journal |first1=Montserrat |last1=Rios |first2=Fani |last2=Tinitana |first3=Pablo |last3=Jarr\u00edn |first4=Natalia |last4=Donoso |first5=Juan Carlos |last5=Romero-Benavides |title=\"Horchata\" drink in Southern Ecuador: medicinal plants and people\u2019s wellbeing |journal=Journal of Ethnobiology and Ethnomedicine |volume=13 |at=article \u211618 |date=9 March 2017 |doi=10.1186/s13002-017-0145-z |doi-access=free }}</ref>\n\n=={{lang|es|Horchata}} as a flavour==\n[[File:Dough-Donut-Horchata.jpg|link=File:Dough-Donut-Horchata.jpg|thumb|A {{lang|es|horchata}}-flavoured [[doughnut]]]]\nHorchata as a flavour makes appearances in ice cream, cookies and other sweets, and other products such as [[RumChata]], an alcoholic tribute to the beverage.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}} Some [[smoothie]] shops, [[caf\u00e9]]s, and McDonald's in the U.S. have been experimenting with horchata-flavoured [[Frapp\u00e9 coffee|frappes]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foodbeast.com/2014/05/12/mcdonalds-testing-horchata-frappes-in-southern-california/ |title=McDonald's Testing Horchata Frappes in Southern California |publisher=[[Foodbeast]] |date=May 12, 2014 |accessdate=July 15, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Etymology==\nThe name derives from [[Valencian language|Valencian]] {{lang|ca-valencia|orxata}}, probably from {{lang|ca-valencia|ordiata}}, made from {{lang|ca-valencia|ordi}} (\"[[barley]]\": Latin {{lang|la|*hordeata}} < {{lang|la|hordeum}}).<ref name=\"Rios et al, 2017\"/> The Italian {{lang|it|orzata}}, the French and English ''[[Orgeat syrup|orgeat]]'' have the [[cognate|same origin]], though the beverages themselves have diverged, and are generally no longer made from barley.<ref>Lobscouse & Spotted Dog: Which It's a Gastronomic Companion to the Aubrey/Maturin Novels : Grossman, Anne Chotzinoff; Thomas, Lisa Grossman {{ISBN|0-393-04559-5}}</ref>\n\nVarious [[etymologies]] exist \u2013 one legend links the origins of the name to [[James I of Aragon]], who, after being given the drink for the first time by a local in [[Alboraya]], was said to have exclaimed in Valencian, \"{{lang|ca-valencia|A\u00e7\u00f2 \u00e9s or, xata!}}\" (\"That's gold, pretty girl!\").<ref>''Valencia & the Costa Blanca'', Miles Roddis, Lonely Planet, 2002, {{ISBN|1-74059-032-5}} [https://books.google.com/books?id=Xs5yVBmuTv4C Google Books]</ref><ref>''MTV Spain'', Fernando Gayesky, Elizabeth Gorman, Kristin Luna, Andre Legaspi, Frommer's, 2007, {{ISBN|0-7645-8772-2}} [https://books.google.com/books?id=Owa_0MppHm4C Google Books]</ref><ref>''Consejo regulador denominaci\u00f3n de origen Chufa de Valencia'',{{cite web|url=http://va.chufadevalencia.org/ver/16/Historia.html|title=Hist\u00f2ria de l'roxata de xufa}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Kunnu aya]]\n* [[Salep]]\n* [[Orgeat syrup]]\n* [[Chicha]]\n* [[Plant milk]]\n** [[Almond milk]]\n** [[Rice milk]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Sister project links |b=Cookbook:Horchata |commons=Category:Horchata |wikt=horchata |d=Q1587937 |n=no|q=no|voy=no|v=no|species=no|s=no }}\n* [http://www.chufadevalencia.org/ The Regulating Council of Denomination of Origin \"Chufa de Valencia\"]: Quality council regulating tiger nut horchata in Valencia\n* [http://www.tastingtable.com/entry_detail/nyc/14262/Horxata_introduces_real_Valencian_horchata_to_NYC.htm Article about Horxata, Ltd.]: Valencian Horchata in New York City\n\n{{Valencian Community topics}}\n{{Mexican cuisine}}\n{{Milk substitutes}}\n{{Rice drinks}}\n\n[[Category:Aguas frescas]]\n[[Category:Plant milk]]\n[[Category:Non-alcoholic drinks]]\n[[Category:Rice drinks]]\n[[Category:Latin American cuisine]]\n[[Category:Mexican drinks]]\n[[Category:Valencian cuisine]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the beverage|the song by Vampire Weekend|Horchata (song)}}\n{{more citations needed|date=December 2018}}\n[[File:Orxatera1.JPG|thumb|right|250px|Traditional Valencian fridge {{lang|es|horchatera}}]]\n\n'''Horchata''' ({{IPAc-en|\u0254r|\u02c8|t\u0283|\u0251\u02d0|t|\u0259}}; {{IPA-es|o\u027e\u02c8t\u0283ata|lang|Horchata.ogg}}), or '''{{lang|ca-valencia|orxata}}''' ({{IPA-va|o\u027e\u02c8\u0283ata|lang}}), is a name given to various kinds of [[plant milk]] beverages of similar taste and appearance. It originated at least as far back as 13th-century [[Valencia]], where it is known as '''{{lang|es|chufa horchata}}'''. In Spain it is made with soaked, ground, and sweetened [[tiger nuts]], but in Mexico and other parts of the Americas the base is white rice.  In [[West Africa]]n countries such as [[Nigeria]] and [[Mali]], it is known as '''{{lang|und|kunnu aya}}.''' Different varieties can be served hot or cold, and it is even used as a flavour in other beverages, such as [[frapp\u00e9 coffee]].\n\n==History and composition==\n[[File:Horchata de chufa 2.jpg|right|thumb|upright|A glass of {{lang|es|horchata de chufa}} in [[Valencia]]]]\n{{lang|es|Horchata}}, which comes from the [[Latin]] term {{lang|la|hordeata}}, which in turn comes from {{lang|la|hordeum}} ([[barley]]), is a term related to a Mediterranean tradition of grain-based beverages and also the linguistic root of [[orgeat syrup]]. The [[Valencia]]n or {{lang|es|Chufa horchata}} is made with dried and sweetened [[tiger nuts]] (''Cyperus esculentus'').<ref name=\"ocss\">{{cite web|url= https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=jbi6BwAAQBAJ&pg=PA341 |title=The Oxford Companion to Sugar and Sweets |first=Darra |last=Goldstein |date=4 July 2018 |publisher= Oxford University Press |via= Google Books}}</ref> This form of horchata is now properly called {{lang|es|horchata de chufa}}<ref name=\"ocss\"/><ref name=\"dietary_fiber_and_health\">{{cite web|url= https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=CWjNBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA433 |title=Dietary Fiber and Health |first1=Susan |last1=Cho |first2=Nelson |last2=Almeida |date=29 May 2012 |publisher=CRC Press| via=Google Books}}</ref> or, in [[West Africa]]n countries such as [[Nigeria]] and [[Mali]], {{lang|und|kunnu aya}}.<ref name=\"dfh\">{{cite web| url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=TJdZI5WZ8k0C&pg=PA433&dq=%22kunnu%22+%22horchata%22 |title=Dietary Fiber and Health |first1=Susan |last1=Cho |first2=Nelson |last2=Almeida |date=29 May 2012 |publisher=CRC Press |via=Google Books}}</ref><ref name=\"newmilks\"/><ref name=\"fatflush\"/> By 1000&nbsp;CE it had spread to [[Hispania]] (now Spain) with the [[Umayyad conquest of Hispania|Muslim conquest]].<ref name=\"ocss\"/> There are 13th-century records of a {{lang|es|horchata}}-like beverage made near Valencia.<ref>Clifford A. Wright, ''Mediterranean Vegetables'', 2012, {{isbn|1558325913}}, ''s.v.'' 'chufa'</ref>\n\nFrom [[Valencia]], where it remained popular, the concept of horchata was brought to the [[New World]]. Here, drinks called {{lang|es|agua de horchata}} or simply {{lang|es|horchata}} came to be made with white rice and cinnamon or {{lang|es|[[canella]]}} instead of tiger nuts.<ref name=\"ocss\"/> Sometimes these drinks had vanilla added,<ref name=\"dietary_fiber_and_health\"/> or were served adorned with fruit.<ref name=\"ocss\"/>\n\nToday, these and other similarly-flavoured plant milk beverages are sold in various parts of the world as varieties of {{lang|es|horchata}} or {{lang|und|kunnu}}.\n\n==Varieties==\n==={{lang|es|Horchata de chufa}} or {{lang|und|kunnu aya}}===\n[[File:ManekiNeko horchata jar.jpg|thumb|upright|Two large jars of {{lang|es|[[aguas frescas]]}} in a [[Seattle]] {{lang|es|[[taquer\u00eda]]}}. On the left is a jar of [[hibiscus tea]] and on the right is a jar of {{lang|es|horchata}}. Restaurant employees serve the drinks by ladling them from the jars into glasses.]]\nThe drink now known as {{lang|es|horchata de chufa}} (also sometimes called {{lang|es|horchata de chufas}}<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/janegrigsonsbook0000grig|url-access=registration|quote=horchata (chufa OR tiger).|title=Jane Grigson's book of European cookery|first=Jane|last=Grigson|date=1 January 1983|publisher=Atheneum|via=Internet Archive}}</ref> or, in West African countries such as Nigeria and Mali, {{lang|und|kunnu aya}}<ref name=\"dfh\"/><ref name=\"newmilks\">{{cite web|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=gAEODAAAQBAJ&pg=PR13|title=The New Milks: 100-Plus Dairy-Free Recipes for Making and Cooking with Soy, Nut, Seed, Grain, and Coconut Milks|first=Dina|last=Cheney|date=3 May 2016|publisher=Simon and Schuster|via=Google Books}}</ref><ref name=\"fatflush\">{{cite web|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Wk-ZDgAAQBAJ&q=%22kunnu%22+%22horchata%22|title=The New Fat Flush Foods|first=Ann Louise|last=Gittleman|date=19 May 2017|publisher=McGraw Hill Professional|via=Google Books}}</ref>) is the original form of horchata.<ref name=\"ocss\"/> It is made from soaked, ground and sweetened [[Cyperus esculentus|tiger nuts]].<ref name=\"ocss\"/> According to researchers at the [[University of Ilorin]], {{lang|und|kunnu}} made from tiger nuts is an inexpensive source of protein.{{Citation needed|date=December 2019|reason=removed citation to predatory publisher content}}\n\nIt remains popular in Spain, where a regulating council exists to ensure the quality and traceability of the product in relation to the [[denominaci\u00f3n de origen|designation of origin]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chufadevalencia.org |title=Consejo Regulador de la D.O. Chufa de Valencia. Horchata de Chufa de Valencia - Portada |publisher=Chufadevalencia.org |date=2002-12-31 |accessdate=2014-07-15}}</ref> There it is served ice-cold as a natural [[wikt:refreshment|refreshment]] in the summer, often served with [[fartons]]. {{lang|es|Horchata de chufa}} is also used instead of dairy milk by the [[lactose intolerance|lactose-intolerant]].{{citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n\nThe majority of the Spanish tiger nut crop is utilised in the production of {{lang|es|horchata de chufa}}.<ref name=\"fst\">{{cite web|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=v9tJAAAAYAAJ&q=horchata+(%22chufa%22+OR+%22tiger%22)&dq=horchata+(%22chufa%22+OR+%22tiger%22)&hl=en|title=Food Science and Technology: Manufacture and distribution of foods|first=James Muil|last=Leitch|date=4 July 1967|publisher=Gordon and Breach|via=Google Books}}</ref> [[Alboraya]] is the most important production centre.<ref name=\"fst\"/>\n\nIn rare instances, various forms of [[aflatoxin]] may be present in {{lang|es|horchata de chufa}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=na28BAAAQBAJ|title=Mycotoxins in Foodstuffs|first=Martin|last=Weidenb\u00f6rner|date=24 January 2014|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\n==={{lang|es|Horchata de arroz}}===\n{{further|Rice milk}}\n[[File:15-07-21-Mexico-Stadtzentrum-RalfR-N3S 9725.jpg|thumb|Hot {{lang|es|horchata}} in Mexico]]\n\n{{lang|es|Horchata de arroz}} is made of [[rice]], sometimes with vanilla and typically with {{lang|es|canella}}<ref name=\"ocss\"/> or [[cinnamon]].<ref name=\"ocss\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.saveur.com/article/Recipes/Horchata-de-Arroz-Tostado |title=Horchata de Arroz Tostado (Toasted Rice Drink) |work=[[Saveur]] }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.saveur.com/article/Recipes/Horchata-de-Arroz-con-Almendras |title=Horchata de Arroz con Almendras (Almond-Rice Drink) |publisher=[[Saveur]] }}</ref>\n\nIt is the most common variety of {{lang|es|horchata}} in [[Mexico]] and [[Guatemala]].{{citation needed|date=July 2018}} In the United States, it is popular in {{lang|es|taquer\u00edas}} and Mexican ice cream shops.<ref>[[Emeril Lagasse]], [http://www.foodnetwork.com/recipes/horchata Horchata Recipe : Food Network] Taste of Mexico, 2007.</ref><ref>[http://www.marthastewart.com/1067306/horchata Horchata Recipe & Video] - Martha Stewart.</ref><ref>[http://www.mexconnect.com/articles/2407-refreshing-rice-drink-horchata-de-arroz Refreshing Rice Drink: Horchata de Arroz] by Karen Hursh Graber 2003 (MexConnect).</ref>\n\nIn [[Alvarado (municipality)|Alvarado]], {{lang|es|horchata de arroz}} is scented with flowers of the Aztec marigold ({{lang|es|cempas\u00fachil}} or ''[[Tagetes erecta]]'').<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=55AERRMRXu0C&pg=PA130|title=Jarocho's Soul: Cultural Identity and Afro-Mexican Dance|first=Anita|last=Gonzalez|date=4 July 2018|publisher=University Press of America|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\nThough {{lang|es|horchata de arroz}} was once typically homemade, it is now available in both ready-to-drink (shelf-stable or refrigerated) and powdered form in grocery stores, principally in the U.S. and Latin America.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n\n{{lang|es|Horchata de arroz}} is one of the three typical drink flavours of [[Mexico|Mexican]] {{lang|es|[[aguas frescas]]}}, together with {{lang|es|[[Tamarindo (drink)|tamarindo]]}} and [[Hibiscus tea|Jamaica]].{{citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n\n==={{lang|es|Horchata de ajonjol\u00ed}}===\n{{lang|es|Horchata de [[wikt:ajonjol\u00ed|ajonjol\u00ed]]}} (\"sesame horchata\") is made with ground sesame seeds.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}} In [[Puerto Rico]], it is typically made by boiling sugar, vanilla, and cinnamon sticks in water, and then pouring the infusion over ground sesame seeds to be left overnight.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}} The mixture is then strained through a [[cheesecloth]].{{citation needed|date=July 2018}} Some recipes call for added ground rice, [[almond meal|ground almonds]], [[evaporated milk]], [[coconut milk]], [[allspice]] and [[rum]],{{citation needed|date=July 2018}} or barley and lime [[zest (ingredient)|zest]].{{citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n\n{{lang|es|Horchata}} is also made with sesame seeds, water and sugar in [[Zulia]], an area in the west of [[Venezuela]].{{citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n\n==={{lang|es|Horchata de mel\u00f3n}}===\n{{lang|es|Horchata de mel\u00f3n}} is made of ground melon seeds.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.los-dos.com/recipes/verarticulo.php?IdArticulo=244485 |title=RECIPE: Horchata |website=Los Dos |access-date=2016-08-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170731000535/http://www.los-dos.com/recipes/verarticulo.php?IdArticulo=244485 |archive-date=2017-07-31 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.saveur.com/article/Recipes/Horchata-de-Melon |title=Horchata de Mel\u00f3n (Cantaloupe Seed Drink) |work=[[Saveur]] }}</ref><ref>[http://www.spokesman.com/stories/2015/apr/29/heavenly-horchata/ Adriana Janovich. \"Heavenly Horchata\" - The Spokesman-Review APRIL 29, 2015]<!--  adrianaj@spokesman.com (509) 459-5446  --></ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://allrecipes.com.mx/receta/5509/horchata-de-semillas-de-mel-n.aspx|title=Horchata de semillas de mel\u00f3n |website=allrecipes.com.mx }}</ref>\n\n==={{lang|es|Semilla de jicaro}}===\nIn the [[Central America]]n countries of [[El Salvador]], [[Nicaragua]], [[Honduras]], and [[Costa Rica]], {{lang|es|horchata}} refers to the drink known as {{lang|es|semilla de jicaro}}, made from [[Crescentia alata|jicaro]] seeds ground with rice and [[spice]]s such as ground [[cocoa bean|cocoa]], cinnamon, sesame seeds, nutmeg, tiger nuts and vanilla.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}} Ground peanuts, almonds and [[cashew]]s may be added.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}} Because of these ingredients, {{lang|es|horchata}} is usually strained before serving.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n\n===Ecuadorian {{lang|es|horchata}}===\nIn [[Ecuador]], {{lang|es|horchata}} is a clear red [[infusion]] of 18 [[herb]]s, and is most famous in the province of [[Loja Province|Loja]].<ref name=\"Rios et al, 2017\">{{cite journal |first1=Montserrat |last1=Rios |first2=Fani |last2=Tinitana |first3=Pablo |last3=Jarr\u00edn |first4=Natalia |last4=Donoso |first5=Juan Carlos |last5=Romero-Benavides |title=\"Horchata\" drink in Southern Ecuador: medicinal plants and people\u2019s wellbeing |journal=Journal of Ethnobiology and Ethnomedicine |volume=13 |at=article \u211618 |date=9 March 2017 |doi=10.1186/s13002-017-0145-z |doi-access=free }}</ref>\n\n=={{lang|es|Horchata}} as a flavour==\n[[File:Dough-Donut-Horchata.jpg|link=File:Dough-Donut-Horchata.jpg|thumb|A {{lang|es|horchata}}-flavoured [[doughnut]]]]\nHorchata as a flavour makes appearances in ice cream, cookies and other sweets, and other products such as [[RumChata]], an alcoholic tribute to the beverage.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}} Some [[smoothie]] shops, [[caf\u00e9]]s, and McDonald's in the U.S. have been experimenting with horchata-flavoured [[Frapp\u00e9 coffee|frappes]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foodbeast.com/2014/05/12/mcdonalds-testing-horchata-frappes-in-southern-california/ |title=McDonald's Testing Horchata Frappes in Southern California |publisher=[[Foodbeast]] |date=May 12, 2014 |accessdate=July 15, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Etymology==\nThe name derives from [[Valencian language|Valencian]] {{lang|ca-valencia|orxata}}, probably from {{lang|ca-valencia|ordiata}}, made from {{lang|ca-valencia|ordi}} (\"[[barley]]\": Latin {{lang|la|*hordeata}} < {{lang|la|hordeum}}).<ref name=\"Rios et al, 2017\"/> The Italian {{lang|it|orzata}}, the French and English ''[[Orgeat syrup|orgeat]]'' have the [[cognate|same origin]], though the beverages themselves have diverged, and are generally no longer made from barley.<ref>Lobscouse & Spotted Dog: Which It's a Gastronomic Companion to the Aubrey/Maturin Novels : Grossman, Anne Chotzinoff; Thomas, Lisa Grossman {{ISBN|0-393-04559-5}}</ref>\n\nVarious [[etymologies]] exist \u2013 one legend links the origins of the name to [[James I of Aragon]], who, after being given the drink for the first time by a local in [[Alboraya]], was said to have exclaimed in Valencian, \"{{lang|ca-valencia|A\u00e7\u00f2 \u00e9s or, xata!}}\" (\"That's gold, pretty girl!\").<ref>''Valencia & the Costa Blanca'', Miles Roddis, Lonely Planet, 2002, {{ISBN|1-74059-032-5}} [https://books.google.com/books?id=Xs5yVBmuTv4C Google Books]</ref><ref>''MTV Spain'', Fernando Gayesky, Elizabeth Gorman, Kristin Luna, Andre Legaspi, Frommer's, 2007, {{ISBN|0-7645-8772-2}} [https://books.google.com/books?id=Owa_0MppHm4C Google Books]</ref><ref>''Consejo regulador denominaci\u00f3n de origen Chufa de Valencia'',{{cite web|url=http://va.chufadevalencia.org/ver/16/Historia.html|title=Hist\u00f2ria de l'roxata de xufa}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Kunnu aya]]\n* [[Salep]]\n* [[Orgeat syrup]]\n* [[Chicha]]\n* [[Plant milk]]\n** [[Almond milk]]\n** [[Rice milk]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Sister project links |b=Cookbook:Horchata |commons=Category:Horchata |wikt=horchata |d=Q1587937 |n=no|q=no|voy=no|v=no|species=no|s=no }}\n* [http://www.chufadevalencia.org/ The Regulating Council of Denomination of Origin \"Chufa de Valencia\"]: Quality council regulating tiger nut horchata in Valencia\n* [http://www.tastingtable.com/entry_detail/nyc/14262/Horxata_introduces_real_Valencian_horchata_to_NYC.htm Article about Horxata, Ltd.]: Valencian Horchata in New York City\n\n{{Valencian Community topics}}\n{{Mexican cuisine}}\n{{Milk substitutes}}\n{{Rice drinks}}\n\n[[Category:Aguas frescas]]\n[[Category:Plant milk]]\n[[Category:Non-alcoholic drinks]]\n[[Category:Rice drinks]]\n[[Category:Latin American cuisine]]\n[[Category:Mexican drinks]]\n[[Category:Valencian cuisine]]\n", "name_user": "2.138.105.157", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Horchata"}
